I"]<p>ASC means Asynchronous Software Component.</p>

<p>Functions are not ASCs.</p>

<p>Functions rely on other - synchronous - functions (and libraries).</p>

<p>The smallest unit of componentization in current PLs<sup id="fnref:1" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:1" class="footnote">1</a></sup> is the <em>thread</em>.</p>

<p><em>Threads</em> typically imply the use of <em>operating systems</em><sup id="fnref:4" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:4" class="footnote">2</a></sup>.</p>

<p>It should be possible to implement “better” (smaller, faster) components using <em>messages</em> and <em>closures</em><sup id="fnref:2" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:2" class="footnote">3</a></sup>.</p>

<p>The main issue is how to structure message-sending components to avoid spaghetti designs.<sup id="fnref:3" role="doc-noteref"><a href="#fn:3" class="footnote">4</a></sup></p>

